Triangle $F_1 F_2 P$ is a right triangle, so by the Pythagorean Theorem,
\[F_1 P = \sqrt{F_1 F_2^2 + F_2 P^2} = \sqrt{8^2 + 4^2} = 4 \sqrt{5}.\]Hence, $F_2 Q - F_1 Q = F_2 P - F_1 P = F_2 P - 4 \sqrt{5},$ so $PQ + F_1 Q = 14 - (F_2 P - 4 \sqrt{5}) = 14 + 4 \sqrt{5} - F_2 P.$  This is maximized when $F_2 P$ is minimized, which occurs when $P$ is the point on the circle closest to $F_2.$  This occurs when $P$ and $F_2$ are on opposite ends of a diameter of the circle, so $F_2 P = 4.$  Therefore, the maximum value is $14 + 4 \sqrt{5} - 4 = \boxed{10 + 4 \sqrt{5}}.$

